I now have all the evidence I need. There is no pre-existing EAP exactly matching this issue — which means this is a novel incident worth cataloging. Here is the complete diagnosis:

---

## Diagnosis

There are **two compounding bugs** in `src/proxy.ts` that together cause `/api/internal/*` requests to bypass the auth gate after the Next.js 16 upgrade. Each one alone would be enough to cause the bypass.

---

## Root Cause

### Bug 1 — The `config.matcher` is exported from the wrong file (Primary)

Next.js requires middleware to live in `src/middleware.ts` (or `middleware.ts` at the project root). The `export const config` with its `matcher` array **must be exported from that file**. Your project exports `proxy()` and `config` from `src/proxy.ts`, which is a regular module, not the Next.js middleware entrypoint.

In **Next.js 15**, the runtime was somewhat forgiving — if `middleware.ts` re-exported from `proxy.ts` and the `config` was visible at module evaluation time, the matcher could bleed through. In **Next.js 16**, the middleware runtime is stricter: it only reads `config.matcher` from the **canonical entrypoint file** (`middleware.ts`). The `config` exported from `proxy.ts` is silently ignored. Without a matcher export in the real `middleware.ts`, Next.js falls back to the framework's built-in exclusion behavior, which explicitly **skips all `/api/*` routes** from middleware by default.

### Bug 2 — The `matcher` pattern doesn't explicitly include `/api/internal/*` (Secondary)

Even if the `config` were read correctly, your current matcher is a *negative-lookahead* pattern — it matches everything *except* static assets:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts — current (broken)
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|sitemap.xml|robots.txt).*)",
  ],
};
```

Next.js 16 adds a new default exclusion for `/api/*` routes from middleware, even when a custom matcher is provided. The rationale is that API route handlers are assumed to manage their own auth. To override this default and force middleware to run on `/api/*` paths, you must **explicitly include them** in your matcher — the negative-lookahead pattern alone is no longer sufficient.

This maps to the broader proxy-allowlist class of issues documented as **EAP-079** — the allowlist (or in this case the matcher) doesn't account for a new path category that must be explicitly declared. There is no exact EAP for the `config` file-split anti-pattern, so this incident warrants a new entry (**candidate EAP**) in `docs/engineering-anti-patterns.md`.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Check your `src/middleware.ts` entrypoint

Verify what `src/middleware.ts` currently looks like:

```ts
// src/middleware.ts — likely current state (broken)
export { proxy as middleware } from "./proxy";
// ❌ Does NOT re-export config — so Next.js 16 sees no matcher
```

Or it may look correct on the surface but not re-export `config`:

```ts
import { proxy } from "./proxy";
export default proxy; // ❌ still missing config
```

### Step 2 — Fix `src/middleware.ts` to own the `config`

The `config` export **must live in `middleware.ts` directly**, not in a helper module. Move it there:

```ts
// src/middleware.ts — FIXED
import { proxy } from "./proxy";

export const middleware = proxy;

// config MUST be in this file — Next.js 16 only reads it from the entrypoint
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    /*
     * Match ALL routes EXCEPT:
     * - Next.js static assets (_next/static, _next/image)
     * - Favicons and standard metadata files
     *
     * Explicitly written as a positive allowlist for /api/* to override
     * Next.js 16's new default exclusion of API routes from middleware.
     */
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon\\.ico|sitemap\\.xml|robots\\.txt).*)",
    "/api/:path*",   // ← explicit include overrides the Next.js 16 API default exclusion
  ],
};
```

### Step 3 — Remove the `config` export from `src/proxy.ts`

It is dead code there and creates the illusion that the matcher is in effect:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts — remove the config export entirely
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
import { verifySessionValue, COOKIE_NAME } from "@/lib/company-session";

export function proxy(request: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = request.nextUrl;

  // Allow login routes through
  if (pathname.startsWith("/for/") || pathname === "/for") {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Allow Payload CMS admin and ALL /api/* routes through
  // (Payload CMS owns /api/* — it has its own auth layer)
  if (pathname.startsWith("/admin") || pathname.startsWith("/api/")) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Allow static assets and Next.js internals
  if (
    pathname.startsWith("/_next/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/images/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/media/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/videos/") ||
    pathname === "/favicon.ico" ||
    pathname === "/robots.txt" ||
    pathname === "/sitemap.xml"
  ) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  const sessionCookie = request.cookies.get(COOKIE_NAME)?.value;
  if (!sessionCookie) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const company = verifySessionValue(sessionCookie);
  if (!company) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const requestHeaders = new Headers(request.headers);
  requestHeaders.set("x-company", company);

  return NextResponse.next({
    request: { headers: requestHeaders },
  });
}

// ❌ DELETE the config export from here — it belongs in middleware.ts only
```

### Step 4 — Verify the fix

```bash
# Confirm middleware.ts re-exports both middleware function and config
grep -n "config" src/middleware.ts

# Test that /api/internal/* is now intercepted (should get a session redirect, not a 200)
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/internal/some-endpoint
# Expect: 307/302 redirect to /for/welcome (no cookie sent)

# Test that /api/* Payload routes still pass through
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/globals/site-config
# Expect: 200 (proxy's /api/* allowlist lets it through)

# Test that a valid session still works end-to-end
# (Use your browser or set the portfolio_session cookie manually)
```

---

## Summary of Changes

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `src/middleware.ts` | Add `export const config = { matcher: [..., "/api/:path*"] }` directly in this file |
| `src/proxy.ts` | Remove the `export const config` block entirely — it was silently dead in Next.js 16 |

---

## Principle

> **`config.matcher` must be colocated with the middleware entrypoint, not in a helper module.** Next.js 16 tightened middleware discovery: it only reads `export const config` from the canonical `middleware.ts` file. Any `config` exported from an imported helper is ignored at runtime with no warning. Coupled with Next.js 16's new default behavior of excluding `/api/*` routes from middleware, a `config` in the wrong file produces a silent total bypass of the auth gate on API routes. This is a variant of **EAP-079** (proxy allowlist not accounting for a new path class) with the added dimension of file-convention strictness — candidate for a new EAP in `docs/engineering-anti-patterns.md`.
